prefix: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in engineering would.
problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in engineering would. What is the molecular weight of CCC1C(=O)NC(=S)S1?
Answer (numerical number):
gpt_response:
The molecular weight of CCC1C(=O)NC(=S)S1 is 136.2 g/mol. 

This can be calculated by adding the atomic weights of each element present in the molecule, accounting for the number of each element present. 

- Carbon (C) has an atomic weight of 12.01 g/mol and there are 3 carbons present, so 3 x 12.01 = 36.03 g/mol
- Nitrogen (N) has an atomic weight of 14.01 g/mol and there is 1 nitrogen present, so 1 x 14.01 = 14.01 g/mol
- Oxygen (O) has an atomic weight of 16.00 g/mol and there is 1 oxygen present, so 1 x 16.00 = 16.00 g/mol
- Sulfur (S) has an atomic weight of 32.07 g/mol and there is 2 sulfur present, so 2 x 32.07 = 64.14 g/mol

Adding these values together, we get 36.03 + 14.01 + 16.00 + 64.14 = 136.2 g/mol as the molecular weight of CCC1C(=O)NC(=S)S1.
